modules.description: The module offers operations for manipulating reactive lists, including inserting, removing, moving elements, concatenating, reversing, and filtering, while maintaining automatic change propagation. It works with reactive data structures that track modifications via signals and patches, enabling efficient updates in event-driven systems. Use cases include real-time data synchronization and dynamic interfaces where downstream dependencies must respond to incremental changes.

The module offers key-based operations for managing ordered maps, including insertion, deletion, and transformation of key-value pairs, alongside traversal and aggregation functions. It works with structured data where keys define order and values are polymorphic, enabling tasks like sorted data processing or dynamic associative storage. Use cases include maintaining ordered dictionaries, efficiently querying extrema, or applying custom transformations to hierarchical datasets.

Provides applicative merge, mapping, and equality operations for structured data, along with patch generation for tracking differences. Works with parameterized data containers and their corresponding patches, enabling safe transformations and comparisons. Used to apply structured updates to data without modifying the original, and to generate minimal change representations between two data states.

Provides operations for tracking and applying incremental changes to data structures using patches, including patch composition, application, and derivation. Works with structured data types such as lists, trees, and records, enabling efficient updates without full recomputation. Used in real-time collaborative editing systems to synchronize changes across multiple users.

Provides operations to create and manipulate reactive containers that automatically update in response to changes. Works with data structures wrapped in handles, patches, and messages, enabling efficient downstream updates. Supports use cases like dynamically updating UI elements based on event streams or signals, and maintaining derived data that reacts to source changes.
